00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:19,000
 for you all making my prayer with joy.

228
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:21,000
 Now that's a really big statement.

229
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:25,000
 In every prayer of Paul's, he's making prayers with joy.

230
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:28,000
 So it begs the question, what's the prayer, Paul?

231
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:31,000
 Like if every prayer you're praying is leading you to be joyful,

232
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:34,000
 then what is it that is actually,

233
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:38,000
 what's actually stirring up your joy for these believers?

234
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:39,000
 Well, verse nine tells us,

235
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:43,000
 and it is my prayer that your love may abound more and more

236
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:45,000
 with knowledge and all discernment,

237
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:47,000
 so that you may approve what is excellent.

238
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:50,000
 And this is the ultimate outcome of prayer.

239
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:54,000
 So be pure and blameless for the day of Christ,

240
00:15:54,000 --> 00:15:55,000
 filled with the fruit of righteousness

241
00:15:55,000 --> 00:15:58,000
 that comes through Jesus Christ to the glory and praise of God.

242
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:00,000
 So what's Paul saying right here?

243
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:02,000
 Well, he's saying a lot, right?

244
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:05,000
 Paul is the master of saying as much as possible

245
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:07,000
 and as few words as possible.

246
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:10,000
 And yet if we could push through all the verbal flourishing

247
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:15,000
 and we could boil this thing down to its most rudimentary summary statement,

248
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:19,000
 what we know is that Paul is simply praying these believers,

249
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:23,000
 as well as you and I, would live with purity and innocence in the world.

250
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:25,000
 That's what he's asking God for.

251
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:27,000
 I don't know what you pray to God for

252
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:30,000
 whenever you're asking him to do something in your life.

253
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:33,000
 Paul is praying for your purity and your innocence.

254
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:35,000
 That's what he cares most about.

255
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:39,000
 He wants us to be a people that think and look and judge,

256
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:42,000
 not like the world, but like God himself.

257
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:44,000
 He actually even doubles down on the idea

258
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:46,000
 whenever you get to the end of his letter.

259
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:49,000
 You turn to Philippians chapter 4, and it says this in verses 8 and 9.

260
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:52,000
 He says, "Finally, brothers, whatever is true, whatever is honorable,

261
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:55,000
 whatever is just, whatever is pure, whatever is lovely,

262
00:16:55,000 --> 00:16:57,000
 whatever is commendable, if there's any excellence,

263
00:16:57,000 --> 00:17:01,000
 if there's anything worthy of praise, think about these things.

264
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:04,000
 What you've learned and received and heard and seen in me,

265
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:06,000
 me as the example, practice these things

266
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:08,000
 and the God of peace will be with you."

267
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:10,000
 Paul is looking at the Philippians and he's saying,

268
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:12,000
 "Hey, I want you to be like me.

269
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:14,000
 I want you to be like me in that I am full of joy."

270
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:17,000
 Like Paul is way better at joy than any of us,

271
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:19,000
 despite the fact that he's lived through things,

272
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:21,000
 the likes of which you and I will probably never know.

273
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:25,000
 The guy is riddled with a holy happiness

274
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:27,000
 that is from heaven on high.

275
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:30,000
 And he's looking at the Philippians and you and saying,

276
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:32,000
 "Hey, I want you to be like me.

277
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:36,000
 I want you to have this indomitable joy, this heavenly happiness."

278
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:41,000
 And the way he advises us to do it is by shifting our perspective.

279
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:48,000
 You see, joy sees through the eyes of innocence.

280
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:50,000
 That's the first point tonight.

281
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:55,000
 Joy sees through the eyes of innocence.

282
00:17:55,000 --> 00:17:57,000
 Like Peter Pan was the one who famously said,

283
00:17:57,000 --> 00:18:00,000
 "Just think happy thoughts and you'll fly."

284
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:03,000
 And the irony is, is that old Peter wasn't far off.

285
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:05,000
 Like to be abundantly clear,

286
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:09,000
 we're not talking about the idea of the power of positive thinking

287
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:11,000
 or the law of attraction,

288
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:14,000
 that if I think something as best for myself,

289
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:18,000
 then I will attract that something that is best for myself to me, myself.

290
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:19,000
 That's not what I'm talking about.

291
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:22,000
 I'm not talking about manifestation as we've modernly described it.

292
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:24,000
 That is actually incongruent with the Bible.

293
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:27,000
 It's actually refuted by the Bible.

294
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:30,000
 That is not a true concept in the slightest.

295
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:34,000
 And yet, what we know is that your thoughts do have power,

296
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:36,000
 not to change your circumstances,

297
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:42,000
 but to transcend your circumstances through a perspective of innocence.

298
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:46,000
 You see, we should see the world in such a way

299
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:50,000
 that relishes the goodness and the beauty

300
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:55,000
 and the truth of God that is on display.

301
00:18:55,000 --> 00:19:02,000
 And yet, what we know is our world does not support that idea in the slightest.

302
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:04,000
 You don't have to look very far to figure it out.

303
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:07,000
 You turn on the TV, you watch the news, you read the critics,

304
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:08,000
 you look through the comments,

305
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:11,000
 and you'll realize our world does not delight in the things

306
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:13,000
 that Paul described in Philippians 4.

307
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:17,000
 Instead, what the world delights in is that which is untrue and dishonorable

308
00:19:17,000 --> 00:19:21,000
 and unjust and impure and unlovely and disgraceful and disappointing

309
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:24,000
 and unpraiseworthy.

310
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:26,000
 Why does the world delight in these things?

311
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:29,000
 Because the world has bought into this crazy idea

312
00:19:29,000 --> 00:19:34,000
 that you have to lose your innocence to become wise.

313
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:37,000
 And yet, what we know is that's the exact same lie

314
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:41,000
 the serpent was saying in the Garden of Eden in Genesis chapter 3.

315
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:44,000
 He looked on the two most innocent people in creation,

316
00:19:44,000 --> 00:19:47,000
 and he simply told them,

317
00:19:47,000 --> 00:19:51,000
 "Wait, doesn't that fruit look desirable to the eyes?

318
00:19:51,000 --> 00:19:55,000
 And isn't it also useful to make you wise?"

319
00:19:55,000 --> 00:19:58,000
 You see, this was the lie from the very beginning,

320
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:01,000
 and it's the lie that our world is perpetrating today.

321
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:04,000
 God knows that when you eat of it, your eyes will be open.

322
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:08,000
 And yet, what we've learned is that it did not replace their innocence with wisdom.

323
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:12,000
 All it did was replace their innocence with guilt.

324
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:14,000
 Some of us can relate to that.

325
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:16,000
 We've bought whatever the world is selling,

326
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:20,000
 and what we feel instead of wisdom and life and fullness

327
00:20:20,000 --> 00:20:23,000
 is we feel guilty.

328
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:26,000
 We feel ashamed.

329
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:29,000
 Our heads hang low. We hope nobody's watching.

330
00:20:29,000 --> 00:20:31,000
 We delete our browser history

331
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:35,000
 because we don't want to actually own up to the things that we've done

332
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:38,000
 in believing the world was telling us the truth.

333
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:43,000
 The world overpromises and underdelivers constantly.

334
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:46,000
 And so what we have to do is we have to stop listening to the world,

335
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:48,000
 and we have to start listening to God.

336
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:51,000
 And what Jesus is saying here by way of his spirit in the Apostle Paul

337
00:20:51,000 --> 00:20:55,000
 is he's saying, "Hey, you have to teach yourself to see things differently."

338
00:20:55,000 --> 00:20:57,000
 As Jesus would put it himself,

339
00:20:57,000 --> 00:21:05,000
 we have to teach ourselves to see things the same way little children do,

340
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:07,000
 which is interesting.

341
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:11,000
 Have you ever wondered to yourself, "Why was Jesus so interested in little kids?"

342
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:14,000
 They were the most inconvenient and insignificant of their day.

343
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:20,000
 Why was he so welcoming and hospitable and inviting to these little kids?

344
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:23,000
 Because he knows something about them that we need to know ourselves.

345
00:21:23,000 --> 00:21:25,000
 He talks about it in Matthew 18. He says this,

346
00:21:25,000 --> 00:21:28,000
 "At that time, the disciples came to Jesus saying,

347
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:30,000
 'Hey, who is the greatest in the kingdom of heaven?'"

348
00:21:30,000 --> 00:21:31,000
 And here's what he did.

349
00:21:31,000 --> 00:21:34,000
 "Calling to him a child, he put him in the midst of them,

350
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:36,000
 and he said, 'Truly I say to you, unless you turn'"

351
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:41,000
 That word is actually often used for repentance.

352
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:46,000
 "If you turn and become like children, you'll never enter the kingdom of heaven.

353
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:51,000
 Whoever humbles himself like this child is the greatest in the kingdom of heaven."

354
00:21:51,000 --> 00:21:56,000
 You see, Jesus welcomed children because of their humility.

355
00:21:56,000 --> 00:21:59,000
 Their humility, like that attitude which expects nothing,

356
00:21:59,000 --> 00:22:02,000
 but it appreciates everything.

357
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:06,000
 Like just as a child depends on another for life,

358
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:12,000
 so too should we depend on God for our life.

359
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:15,000
 But it's not just that a child depends on another for life.

360
00:22:15,000 --> 00:22:22,000
 It's also that children delight with one another in life.

361
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:24,000
 We should be similar.

362
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:29,000
 We should look just like kids into the world for all reasons to rejoice.

363
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:31,000
 And the beauty of children is it doesn't take them much

364
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:34,000
 to actually find reason to have fun,

365
00:22:34,000 --> 00:22:37,000
 to actually gain good cause for celebration,

366
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:42,000
 to actually identify a plausible excuse for play.

367
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:47,000
 I remember reading a part of Lonnie Johnson's story.

368
00:22:47,000 --> 00:22:51,000
 Lonnie was a scientist with the NASA Jet Propulsion Lab

369
00:22:51,000 --> 00:22:53,000
 during the historic Galileo mission.

370
00:22:53,000 --> 00:22:57,000
 He was working on a new jet pump design at home one day

371
00:22:57,000 --> 00:23:00,000
 when he accidentally shot a stream of water across his bathroom.

372
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:02,000
 Thinking he might be onto something special,

373
00:23:02,000 --> 00:23:06,000
 but wanting to test the marketability of his mistake,

374
00:23:06,000 --> 00:23:12,000
 he eventually built his seven-year-old daughter a prototype jet pump.

375
00:23:12,000 --> 00:23:14,000
 And he gave it to her, and he told her to take it

376
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:18,000
 and show it to her friends and see what they said.

377
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:23,000
 What he learned is that he had the most fortuitous accident

378
00:23:23,000 --> 00:23:28,000
 because the super soaker was born.

379
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:37,000
 He was able to design one of the top 20 most widely known

380
00:23:37,000 --> 00:23:41,000
 and broadly sold toys in American history

381
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:44,000
 because he handed it to a kid.

382
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:49,000
 And he asked her to test its marketability,

383
00:23:49,000 --> 00:23:53,000
 to figure out if it actually was worthy of rejoicing in.

384
00:23:53,000 --> 00:23:56,000
 You see, there's a lot we can learn from little kids.

385
00:23:56,000 --> 00:24:00,000
 G.K. Chesterton says it like this,

386
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:04,000
 "Because children have abounding vitality,

387
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:07,000
 because they are in spirit fierce and free,

388
00:24:07,000 --> 00:24:09,000
 therefore they want things repeated and unchanged.

389
00:24:09,000 --> 00:24:11,000
 They always say, 'Do it again!'

390
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:16,000
 And the grown-up person does it again until he is nearly dead."

391
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:22,000
 For grown-up people are not strong enough to exult in monotony,

392
00:24:22,000 --> 00:24:26,000
 but perhaps God is strong enough to exult in monotony.

393
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:28,000
 It is possible that God says every morning,

394
00:24:28,000 --> 00:24:30,000
 "Do it again" to the sun,

395
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:33,000
 and every evening, "Do it again" to the moon.

396
00:24:33,000 --> 00:24:38,000
 It may not be the automatic necessity that makes all daisies alike.

397
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:42,000
 It may be that God makes every daisy separately

398
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:45,000
 but has never got tired of making them.

399
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:49,000
 It may be that he has the eternal appetite of infancy.

400
00:24:49,000 --> 00:24:53,000
 For we have sinned and grown old,

401
00:24:53,000 --> 00:24:56,000
 and our Father is younger than we."

402
00:24:56,000 --> 00:25:02,000
 You see, joy sees the world through the eyes of innocence.

403
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:04,000
 But let me be clear,

404
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:08,000
 not with a childish faith,

405
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:11,000
 but a childlike faith.

406
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:13,000
 There's a big difference in those two ideas.

407
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:16,000
 Paul's instruction is not that we would not be

408
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:18,000
 full of knowledge and understanding.

409
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:20,000
 He actually says quite the opposite in chapter 1.

410
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:23,000
 No, we should be well-informed,

411
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:27,000
 and yet we should receive that information with delight.

412
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:29,000
 It should lead us to engage the world

413
00:25:29,000 --> 00:25:31,000
 in the way that it was meant to be engaged,

414
00:25:31,000 --> 00:25:37,000
 with the kind of delight that doesn't just rejoice

415
00:25:37,000 --> 00:25:41,000
 when a sunset catches you off unexpectedly,

416
00:25:41,000 --> 00:25:45,000
 or when a long-lost friend calls you because they want to reconcile,

417
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:49,000
 or because the opportunity of a lifetime has come for you to travel across the world.

418
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:52,000
 That's not the only moment when we're meant to engage with joy.

419
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:54,000
 Yes, those moments come.

420
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:57,000
 They are quite significant, and we should certainly rejoice in them.

421
00:25:57,000 --> 00:26:00,000
 And yet what we know from children is they don't need significance.

422
00:26:00,000 --> 00:26:03,000
 They need insignificance to rejoice in.

423
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:06,000
 We know that children, as the example here,

424
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:10,000
 those that are most characteristically innocent,

425
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:13,000
 they find beauty and goodness and truth and splendor

426
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:18,000
 where it's most frequently found in simplicity.

427
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:22,000
 You don't have to wait until you take that trip to Cabo to find joy,

428
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:27,000
 because joy is waiting for you tonight.

429
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:30,000
 It isn't rooted in what you experience in life.

430
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:37,000
 It is rooted in how you experience life.

431
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:38,000
 That's the first point.

432
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:42,000
 Paul wants us to develop an instinct for innocence.

433
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:43,000
 We need to move very quickly.

434
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:45,000
 So here we go.

435
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:48,000
 Chapter 2. Paul keeps going.

436
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:50,000
 He says this in verse 14.

437
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:53,000
 "Do all things without grumbling or disputing,

438
00:26:53,000 --> 00:26:55,000
 that you may be blameless and innocent."

439
00:26:55,000 --> 00:26:57,000
 There's that language again.

440
00:26:57,000 --> 00:27:01,000
 "Children of God, without blemish in the midst of a crooked and twisted generation,"

441
00:27:01,000 --> 00:27:03,000
 which is the opposite of innocence, is it not?

442
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:05,000
 "Among whom you shine as lights in the world,

443
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:07,000
 holding fast to the word of light,

444
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:09,000
 so that in the day of Christ I may be proud

445
00:27:09,000 --> 00:27:12,000
 that I did not run in vain or labor in vain.

446
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:14,000
 Even if I am to be poured out as a drink offering

447
00:27:14,000 --> 00:27:16,000
 upon the sacrificial offering of your faith,

448
00:27:16,000 --> 00:27:19,000
 I am glad and I rejoice with you all.

449
00:27:19,000 --> 00:27:24,000
 Likewise, you also should be glad and rejoice with me."

450
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:27,000
 What is the source of Paul's joy right here?

451
00:27:27,000 --> 00:27:30,000
 It's the confidence in what they do in life.

452
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:34,000
 He started off by saying, "Hey, my joy is rooted in your innocence,"

453
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:38,000
 but now he continues and he says, "My joy is found in your obedience."

454
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:40,000
 Which if I had to guess, catches some of us off guard

455
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:42,000
 and leaves some of us slightly annoyed

456
00:27:42,000 --> 00:27:45,000
 because this is so typical of religion.

457
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:47,000
 Of course, this is what he would say.

458
00:27:47,000 --> 00:27:50,000
 He would want us to do this to get that.

459
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:51,000
 It's the spiritual vending machine.

460
00:27:51,000 --> 00:27:53,000
 I drop in X and I get out Y.

461
00:27:53,000 --> 00:27:56,000
 But listen, that is not the heart of the gospel.

462
00:27:56,000 --> 00:28:00,000
 Jesus is not interested in a transactional relationship with you.

463
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:02,000
 He doesn't want a quid pro quo type of arrangement

464
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:04,000
 where, "Hey, I'll give you this if you give me that."

465
00:28:04,000 --> 00:28:06,000
 That's not his heart in the slightest.

466
00:28:06,000 --> 00:28:08,000
 You see, God, and this is so important,

467
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:15,000
 he does not command of you because he is trying to make you good.

468
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:22,000
 God commands of you because he is inviting you into his goodness.

469
00:28:22,000 --> 00:28:24,000
 That is huge.

470
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:26,000
 He's not trying to just make you good.

471
00:28:26,000 --> 00:28:30,000
 He is trying to bring you into his goodness.

472
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:32,000
 Like every command and every statute and every instruction

473
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:34,000
 and all of the rules, he's saying,

474
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:36,000
 "Hey, this is the way to joy.

